        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Mediation in Africa</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Angolan President Joao Lourenco confirmed a meeting for peace talks between the DRC and M23 rebel groups.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and the M23 rebel group will meet for <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-03-2025-h3-3-peace-talks-in-angola" target="_blank">peace talks in Angola</a> on March 18. This is progress from Congo‚Äôs earlier stance, which refused direct negotiations. Angolan President Joao Lourenco confirmed the meeting as part of ongoing mediation efforts. According to the United Nations refugee agency, nearly 80,000 people have fled the country due to the armed conflict.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Congo‚Äôs PM, Judith Suminwa Tuluka, insists Rwanda is responsible for violating the country‚Äôs sovereignty while accusing it of backing M23. Rwanda denies the allegation. The conflict has intensified since January, with M23 seizing the strategic city of Goma. Suminwa Tuluka estimates over 7,000 people have died in recent months, though independent verification is lacking.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">M23, active in eastern Congo since 2012, has also been accused of targeting journalists, a claim the group denies. International pressure is mounting on the upcoming talks, which offer a rare opportunity to de-escalate violence in the mineral-rich region. However, deep-rooted tensions make it difficult to achieve lasting peace.</p>
        </mj-text>
