            <strong>üá™üá® Ecuador enlists founder of Blackwater private army as ally in ‚Äòwar‚Äô on crime</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Ecuador's President Daniel Noboa has announced a strategic alliance with Erik Prince, the founder of Blackwater, a private American defense mercenary, to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-03-2025-br1-4-combat-narco-terrorism" target="_blank">combat narco-terrorism</a> and illegal fishing. This partnership is part of Noboa‚Äôs tough approach to crime as he seeks re-election in the April 13 presidential run-off. Noboa has launched a crackdown on gangs and cartels, calling it a "war" against crime.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">His efforts have faced criticism for human rights abuses and failing to reduce violence in the country. Ecuador still serves as a key drug trafficking route between Colombia and Peru. Prince‚Äôs involvement has sparked backlash due to Blackwater‚Äôs controversial history, including the 2007 killing of Iraqi civilians. The deal raises concerns about the use of paramilitary tactics and increased repression in Ecuador.</p>
